# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: unreal-engine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] The principal designers of the C# programming language were Anders Hejlsberg, Scott Wiltamuth, and Peter Golde from Microsoft.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] It was first widely distributed in July 2000 and was later approved as an international standard by Ecma (ECMA-334) in 2002 and ISO/IEC (ISO/IEC 23270 and 20619) in 2003.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft introduced C# along with .NET Framework and Microsoft Visual Studio, both of which are, technically speaking, closed-source.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] At the time, Microsoft had no open-source products.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Four years later, in 2004, a free and open-source project called Mono began, providing a cross-platform compiler and runtime environment for the C# programming language.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] A decade later, Microsoft released Visual Studio Code (code editor), Roslyn (compiler), and the unified .NET platform (software framework), all of which support C# and are free, open-source, and cross-platform.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Mono also joined Microsoft, but was not merged into .NET.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] As of November 2025, the most recent stable version of the language is C# 14.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] During the development of the .NET Framework, the class libraries were originally written using a managed code compiler system named *Simple Managed C* (SMC).
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] In January 1999, Anders Hejlsberg formed a team to build a new language at the time called COOL, which stood for "C-like Object Oriented Language".
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft had considered keeping the name "COOL(C-like Object Oriented Language)" as the final name of the language, but chose not to do so for trademark reasons.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] By the time the .NET project was publicly announced at the July 2000 Professional Developers Conference, the language had been renamed C#, and the class libraries and ASP.NET runtime were ported to C#.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Hejlsberg was C#'s principal designer and lead architect at Microsoft, and had been previously involved with the design of Turbo Pascal, Embarcadero Delphi (formerly CodeGear Delphi, Inprise Delphi and Borland Delphi), and Visual J++.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] In interviews and technical papers, he has stated that flaws in most major programming languages (e.g.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] C++, Java, Delphi, and Smalltalk) drove the fundamentals of the Common Language Runtime (CLR), which, in turn, drove the design of the C# language.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] In July 2000, Hejlsberg said that C# is "not a Java clone" and is "much closer to C++" in its design.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Since the release of C# 2.0 in November 2005, the C# and Java languages have evolved on increasingly divergent trajectories, becoming two quite different languages.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] One of the first major departures came with the addition of generics to both languages, with vastly different implementations.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] C# uses reification to provide "first-class" generic objects that can be used like any other class, with code generation performed at class-load time.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] C# has also added several major features to accommodate functional-style programming, culminating in the LINQ extensions released with C# 3.0 and its supporting framework of lambda expressions, extension methods, and anonymous types.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] These features enable C# programmers to use functional programming techniques, such as closures, when it is advantageous to their application.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] C# used to have a mascot called Andy (named after Anders Hejlsberg).
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] C# was originally submitted to the ISO/IEC JTC 1 subcommittee SC 22 for review, under ISO/IEC 23270:2003, was withdrawn and was then approved under ISO/IEC 23270:2006.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] The 23270:2006 is withdrawn under 23270:2018 and approved with this version.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft first used the name C# in 1988 for a variant of the C language designed for incremental compilation.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] That project was not completed, and the name was later reused.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] The name "C sharp" was inspired by the musical notation whereby a sharp symbol indicates that the written note should be made a semitone higher in pitch.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] This is similar to the language name of C++, where "++" indicates that a variable should be incremented by 1 after being evaluated.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] The sharp symbol also resembles a ligature of four "+" symbols (in a two-by-two grid), further implying that the language is an increment of C++.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Due to technical limits of display (standard fonts, browsers, etc.), and most keyboard layouts lacking a sharp symbol (U+266F ♯ MUSIC SHARP SIGN (&sharp;)), the number sign (U+0023 # NUMBER SIGN (&num;)) was chosen to approximate the sharp symbol in the written name of the programming language.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] This convention is reflected in the ECMA-334 C# Language Specification.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] The "sharp" suffix has been used by a number of other Microsoft .NET compatible/compliant languages that are variants of existing languages, including J# (a .NET language also designed by Microsoft that is derived from Java 1.1), A# (from Ada), and the functional programming language F#.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] The original implementation of Eiffel for .NET was called Eiffel#, a name retired since the full Eiffel language is now supported.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] The suffix has also been used for libraries, such as Gtk# (a .NET wrapper for GTK and other GNOME libraries) and Cocoa# (a wrapper for Cocoa).
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Development of the text for standards (beginning with C# 6) is done on GitHub.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] C# 7 was submitted to Ecma and approved in December 2023.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] As of January 2024, the standard for C# 8 is currently under development, referencing the approved language proposals.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] By design, C# is the programming language that most directly reflects the underlying Common Language Infrastructure (CLI).
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Most of its intrinsic types correspond to value-types implemented by the CLI framework.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] However, the language specification does not state the code generation requirements of the compiler: that is, it does not state that a C# compiler must target a Common Language Runtime (CLR), or generate Common Intermediate Language (CIL), or generate any other specific format.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Some C# compilers can also generate machine code like traditional compilers of Objective-C, C, C++, Assembly and Fortran.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] C# supports strongly, implicitly typed variable declarations with the keyword `var`, and implicitly typed arrays with the keyword `new[]` followed by a collection initializer.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Due to their special handling of the equality operator and their immutability, strings will nevertheless behave as if they were values, for all practical purposes.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] The programmer can even use them as case labels.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Where necessary, value types will be boxed automatically.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] C# supports a strict Boolean data type, `bool`.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Statements that take conditions, such as `while` and `if`, require an expression of a type that evaluates to the `true` boolean value.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] While C++ also has a Boolean type, it can be freely converted to and from integers, and expressions such as `if (a)` require only that `a` is convertible to bool, allowing `a` to be an int, or a pointer.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] C# disallows this "integer meaning true or false" approach, on the grounds that forcing programmers to use expressions that return exactly `bool` can prevent certain types of programming mistakes such as `if (a = b)` (use of assignment `=` instead of equality `==`).
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] The only implicit conversions by default are those that are considered safe, such as widening of integers.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] This is enforced at compile-time, during Just-in-time compilation, and, in some cases, at runtime.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] No implicit conversions occur between Booleans and integers, nor between enumeration members and integers (except for literal 0, which can be implicitly converted to any enumerated type).
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Any user-defined conversion must be explicitly marked as explicit or implicit, unlike C++ copy constructors and conversion operators, which are both implicit by default.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] C# has explicit support for covariance and contravariance in generic types, unlike C++ which has some degree of support for contravariance simply through the semantics of return types on virtual methods.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Enumeration members are placed in their own scope.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] The C# language does not allow for global variables or functions.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] All methods and members must be declared within classes.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Static members of public classes can substitute for global variables and functions.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Local variables cannot shadow variables of the enclosing block, unlike C and C++, but may shadow type-level names.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] A *method* in C# is a member of a class that can be invoked as a function, rather than the mere value-holding capability of a *field*, i.e., class or instance variable.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Different from most other languages, call-by-reference parameters have to be marked both at the function definition and at the calling site, and the programmer can choose between `ref` and `out`, the latter allowing handing over an uninitialized variable which will have a definite value on return.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Additionally, the programmer can specify a variable-sized argument list by applying the `params` keyword to the last parameter.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Certain specific kinds of methods, such as those that simply get or set a field's value by returning or assigning it, do not require an explicitly stated full signature, but in the general case, the definition of a class includes the full signature declaration of its methods.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Like C++, and unlike Java, C# programmers must use the scope modifier keyword `virtual` to allow methods to be overridden by subclasses.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike C++, the programmer must explicitly specify the keyword `override` when doing so.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] This is supposed to avoid confusion between overriding and newly overloading a function, i.e., hiding the former implementation.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] To do the latter, the programmer has to specify the `new` keyword.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] The keyword `sealed` can be used to disallow further overrides for individual methods or whole classes.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] The type `dynamic` allows for run-time method binding, allowing for JavaScript-like method calls and run-time object composition.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] C# has support for strongly-typed function pointers via the keyword `delegate`.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Like the Qt framework's pseudo-C++ *signal* and *slot*, C# has semantics specifically surrounding publish-subscribe style events, though C# uses delegates to do so.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike fields, `event` variables can be part of an interface, because they technically consist of two default functions to add and remove to-be-called delegates.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] C# offers Java-like `synchronized` method calls, via the attribute `[MethodImpl(MethodImplOptions.Synchronized)]`, and has support for mutually-exclusive locks via the keyword `lock`.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] The properties can be simple accessor functions with a backing field, or implement arbitrary getter and setter functions.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] A property is read-only if there's no setter.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Like with fields, there can be class and instance properties.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] The underlying methods can be `virtual` or `abstract` like any other method.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Since C# 3.0 the syntactic sugar of auto-implemented properties is available, where the accessor (getter) and mutator (setter) encapsulate operations on a single field of a class.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] A C# `namespace` provides the same level of code isolation as a Java `package` or a C++ `namespace`, with rules and features very similar to a `package`.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Namespaces can be imported with the "using" syntax.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] In C#, memory address pointers can only be used within blocks specifically marked as *unsafe*, and programs with unsafe code need appropriate permissions to run.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Most object access is done through safe object references, which always either point to a "live" object or have the well-defined null value; it is impossible to obtain a reference to a "dead" object (one that has been garbage collected), or to an arbitrary block of memory.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] An unsafe pointer can point to an instance of an unmanaged value type that does not contain any references to objects subject to garbage collections such as class instances, arrays or strings.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Code that is not marked as unsafe can still store and manipulate pointers through the `System.IntPtr` type, but it cannot dereference them.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Managed memory cannot be explicitly freed; instead, it is automatically garbage collected.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Garbage collection addresses the problem of memory leaks by freeing the programmer of responsibility for releasing memory that is no longer needed in most cases.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Code that retains references to objects longer than is required can still experience higher memory usage than necessary, however once the final reference to an object is released the memory is available for garbage collection.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] A range of standard exceptions are available to programmers.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Methods in standard libraries regularly throw system exceptions in some circumstances and the range of exceptions thrown is normally documented.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Custom exception classes can be defined for classes allowing handling to be put in place for particular circumstances as needed.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] This is usually called a "try-catch" code block, because of the "try" and "catch" functions being used and accessible on all C# versions.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] If inspecting the error details is not required, the `(Exception ex)` parameter can be omitted as well.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Also, there can be several "catch" parts handling different kinds of exceptions.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Checked exceptions are not present in C# (in contrast to Java).
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] This has been a conscious decision based on the issues of scalability and version management.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike C++, C# does not support multiple inheritance, although a class can implement any number of "interfaces" (fully abstract classes).
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] This was a design decision by the language's lead architect to avoid complications and to simplify architectural requirements throughout CLI.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] When implementing multiple interfaces that contain a method with the same name and taking parameters of the same types in the same order, i.e., the same signature, similar to Java, C# allows both a single method to cover all interfaces and, if necessary, specific methods for each interface.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] C# also offers function overloading (a.k.a. ad-hoc-polymorphism), i.e., methods with the same name, but distinguishable signatures.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike Java, C# additionally supports operator overloading.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Since version 2.0, C# offers parametric polymorphism, i.e., classes with arbitrary or constrained type parameters, e.g., `List<T>`, a variable-sized array which only can contain elements of type `T`.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] There are certain kinds of constraints the programmer can specify for the type parameters: Has to be type X (or one derived from it), has to implement a certain interface, has to be a reference type, has to be a value type, has to implement a public parameterless constructor.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Most of them can be combined, and any number of interfaces can be specified.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] C# has the ability to utilize LINQ through the .NET Framework.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] A developer can query a variety of data sources, provided the `IEnumerable<T>` interface is implemented on the object.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] This includes XML documents, an ADO.NET dataset, and SQL databases.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Using LINQ in C# brings advantages like IntelliSense support, strong filtering capabilities, type safety with compile error checking ability, and consistency for querying data over a variety of sources.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] There are several different language structures that can be utilized with C# and LINQ and they are query expressions, lambda expressions, anonymous types, implicitly typed variables, extension methods, and object initializers.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] LINQ has two syntaxes: query syntax and method syntax.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] However, the compiler always converts the query syntax to method syntax at compile time.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] This unified type system is called Common Type System (CTS).
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] A unified type system implies that all types, including primitives such as integers, are subclasses of the `System.Object` class.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] For example, every type inherits a `ToString()` method.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Instances of value types neither have referential identity nor referential comparison semantics.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Equality and inequality comparisons for value types compare the actual data values within the instances, unless the corresponding operators are overloaded.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Value types are derived from `System.ValueType`, always have a default value, and can always be created and copied.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Other examples are `enum` (enumerations) and `struct` (user defined structures).
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] In contrast, reference types have the notion of referential identity, meaning that each instance of a reference type is inherently distinct from every other instance, even if the data within both instances is the same.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] This is reflected in default equality and inequality comparisons for reference types, which test for referential rather than structural equality, unless the corresponding operators are overloaded (such as the case for `System.String`).
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Some operations are not always possible, such as creating an instance of a reference type, copying an existing instance, or performing a value comparison on two existing instances.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Nevertheless, specific reference types can provide such services by exposing a public constructor or implementing a corresponding interface (such as `ICloneable` or `IComparable`).
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Examples of reference types are `object` (the ultimate base class for all other C# classes), `System.String` (a string of Unicode characters), and `System.Array` (a base class for all C# arrays).
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Both type categories are extensible with user-defined types.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] The C# specification details a minimum set of types and class libraries that the compiler expects to have available.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] In practice, C# is most often used with some implementation of the Common Language Infrastructure (CLI), which is standardized as ECMA-335 *Common Language Infrastructure (CLI)*.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] In addition to the standard CLI specifications, there are many commercial and community class libraries that build on top of the .NET framework libraries to provide additional functionality.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] C# can make calls to any library included in the List of .NET libraries and frameworks.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] The line above imports all types in the `System` namespace.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] For example, the `Console` class used later in the source code is defined in the `System` namespace, meaning it can be used without supplying the full name of the type (which includes the namespace).
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] This line is a comment; it describes and documents the code for the programmer(s).
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Above is a class definition for the `Program` class.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Everything that follows between the pair of braces describes that class.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] The curly brackets demarcate the boundaries of a code block.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] In this first instance, they are marking the start and end of the `Program` class.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] This declares the class member method where the program begins execution.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] The .NET runtime calls the `Main` method.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike in Java, the `Main` method does not need the `public` keyword, which tells the compiler that the method can be called from anywhere by any class.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Writing `static void Main(string[] args)` is equivalent to writing `private static void Main(string[] args)`.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] The static keyword makes the method accessible without an instance of `Program`.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Each console application's `Main` entry point must be declared `static` otherwise the program would require an instance of `Program`, but any instance would require a program.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] To avoid that irresolvable circular dependency, C# compilers processing console applications (like that above) report an error if there is no `static Main` method.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] The `void` keyword declares that `Main` has no return value.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] `Console` is a static class in the `System` namespace.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] It provides an interface to the standard input/output, and error streams for console applications.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] The program calls the `Console` method `WriteLine`, which displays on the console a line with the argument, the string `"Hello, World!"`.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] With .NET 2.0 and C# 2.0, the community got more flexible collections than those in .NET 1.x.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] In the absence of generics, developers had to use collections such as ArrayList to store elements as objects of unspecified kind, which incurred performance overhead when boxing/unboxing/type-checking the contained items.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Generics introduced a massive new feature in .NET that allowed developers to create type-safe data structures.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] This shift is particularly important in the context of converting legacy systems, where updating to generics can significantly enhance performance and maintainability by replacing outdated data structures with more efficient, type-safe alternatives.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] In August 2001, Microsoft, Hewlett-Packard and Intel co-sponsored the submission of specifications for C# as well as the Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) to the standards organization Ecma International.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] In December 2001, ECMA released ECMA-334 *C# Language Specification*.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] C# became an ISO/IEC standard in 2003 (ISO/IEC 23270:2003 - *Information technology — Programming languages — C#*).
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] ECMA had previously adopted equivalent specifications as the 2nd edition of C#, in December 2002.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] In June 2005, ECMA approved edition 3 of the C# specification, and updated ECMA-334.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Additions included partial classes, anonymous methods, nullable types, and generics (somewhat similar to C++ templates).
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] In July 2005, ECMA submitted to ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22, via the latter's Fast-Track process, the standards and related TRs.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] The C# language definition and the CLI are standardized under ISO/IEC and Ecma standards that provide reasonable and non-discriminatory licensing protection from patent claims.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft initially agreed not to sue open-source developers for violating patents in non-profit projects for the part of the framework that is covered by the Open Specification Promise.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft has also agreed not to enforce patents relating to Novell products against Novell's paying customers with the exception of a list of products that do not explicitly mention C#, .NET or Novell's implementation of .NET (The Mono Project).
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] However, Novell maintained that Mono does not infringe any Microsoft patents.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft also made a specific agreement not to enforce patent rights related to the Moonlight browser plugin, which depends on Mono, provided it is obtained through Novell.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] A decade later, Microsoft began developing free, open-source, and cross-platform tooling for C#, namely Visual Studio Code, .NET Core, and Roslyn.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Mono joined Microsoft as a project of Xamarin, a Microsoft subsidiary.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft has developed open-source reference C# compilers and tools.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] The first compiler, Roslyn, compiles into intermediate language (IL), and the second one, RyuJIT, is a JIT (just-in-time) compiler, which is dynamic and does on-the-fly optimization and compiles the IL into native code for the front-end of the CPU.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] RyuJIT is open source and written in C++.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Roslyn is entirely written in managed code (C#), has been opened up and functionality surfaced as APIs.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] It is thus enabling developers to create refactoring and diagnostics tools.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] Two branches of official implementation are .NET Framework (closed-source, Windows-only) and .NET Core (open-source, cross-platform); they eventually converged into one open-source implementation: .NET 5.0.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] At .NET Framework 4.6, a new JIT compiler replaced the former.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] The Unity game engine uses C# as its primary scripting language.
[src:unreal-engine/c-sharp-programming-language] The Godot game engine has implemented an optional C# module due to a donation of $24,000 from Microsoft.
[src:unreal-engine/deferred-shading] In the field of 3D computer graphics, **deferred shading** is a screen-space shading technique that is performed on a second rendering pass, after the vertex and pixel shaders are rendered.
[src:unreal-engine/deferred-shading] It was first suggested by Michael Deering in 1988.
[src:unreal-engine/deferred-shading] On the first pass of a deferred shader, only data that is required for shading computation is gathered.
[src:unreal-engine/deferred-shading] Positions, normals, and materials for each surface are rendered into the geometry buffer (G-buffer) using "render to texture".
[src:unreal-engine/deferred-shading] After this, a pixel shader computes the direct and indirect lighting at each pixel using the information of the texture buffers in screen space.
[src:unreal-engine/deferred-shading] Screen space directional occlusion can be made part of the deferred shading pipeline to give directionality to shadows and interreflections.
[src:unreal-engine/deferred-shading] The primary advantage of deferred shading is the decoupling of scene geometry from lighting.
[src:unreal-engine/deferred-shading] Only one geometry pass is required, and each light is only computed for those pixels that it actually affects.
[src:unreal-engine/deferred-shading] This gives the ability to render many lights in a scene without a significant performance hit.
[src:unreal-engine/deferred-shading] There are some other advantages claimed for the approach.
[src:unreal-engine/deferred-shading] These include simpler management of complex lighting resources, ease of managing other complex shader resources, and the simplification of the software rendering pipeline.
[src:unreal-engine/deferred-shading] One key disadvantage of deferred rendering is the inability to handle transparency within the algorithm, although this problem is a generic one in Z-buffered scenes and it tends to be handled by delaying and sorting the rendering of transparent portions of the scene.
[src:unreal-engine/deferred-shading] Depth peeling can be used to achieve order-independent transparency in deferred rendering, but at the cost of additional batches and g-buffer size.
[src:unreal-engine/deferred-shading] Modern hardware, supporting DirectX 10 and later, is often capable of performing batches fast enough to maintain interactive frame rates.
[src:unreal-engine/deferred-shading] When order-independent transparency is desired (commonly for consumer applications) deferred shading is no less effective than forward shading using the same technique.
[src:unreal-engine/deferred-shading] Another serious disadvantage is the difficulty with using multiple materials.
[src:unreal-engine/deferred-shading] It's possible to use many different materials, but it requires more data to be stored in the G-buffer, which is already quite large and takes up a large amount of the memory bandwidth.
[src:unreal-engine/deferred-shading] One more disadvantage is that, due to separating the lighting stage from the geometric stage, hardware anti-aliasing does not produce correct results anymore since interpolated subsamples would result in nonsensical position, normal, and tangent attributes.
[src:unreal-engine/deferred-shading] Although it is not an edge-smoothing technique, temporal anti-aliasing (used in *Halo: Reach and Unreal Engine*) can also help give edges a smoother appearance.
[src:unreal-engine/deferred-shading] DirectX 10 introduced features allowing shaders to access individual samples in multi-sampled render targets (and depth buffers in version 10.1), giving users of this API access to hardware anti-aliasing in deferred shading.
[src:unreal-engine/deferred-shading] These features also allow them to correctly apply HDR luminance mapping to anti-aliased edges, where in earlier versions of the API any benefit of anti-aliasing may have been lost.
[src:unreal-engine/deferred-shading] Use of the technique has increased in video games because of the control it enables in terms of using a large amount of dynamic lights and reducing the complexity of required shader instructions.
[src:unreal-engine/deferred-shading] In comparison to deferred lighting, this technique is not very popular due to high memory size and bandwidth requirements, especially on seventh generation consoles where graphic memory size and bandwidth are limited and often bottlenecks.
[src:unreal-engine/deferred-shading] The idea of deferred shading was originally introduced by Michael Deering and his colleagues in a paper published in 1988 titled *The triangle processor and normal vector shader: a VLSI system for high performance graphics*.
[src:unreal-engine/deferred-shading] Although the paper never uses the word "deferred", a key concept is introduced; each pixel is shaded only once after depth resolution.
[src:unreal-engine/deferred-shading] Deferred shading as we know it today, using G-buffers, was introduced in a paper by Saito and Takahashi in 1990, although they too do not use the word "deferred".
[src:unreal-engine/deferred-shading] The first deferred shaded video game was *Shrek*, an Xbox launch title shipped in 2001.
[src:unreal-engine/deferred-shading] Around 2004, implementations on commodity graphics hardware started to appear.
[src:unreal-engine/deferred-shading] The technique later gained popularity for applications such as video games, finally becoming mainstream around 2008 to 2010.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] A **game engine** is a software framework primarily designed for video game development, which may include specialized software libraries and packages, such as level editors.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] The term "engine" is a direct analogue of "software engine", having it employed across sectors of the software industry.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Furthermore, *game engine* may also refer to the integrated development environment as an interface behind the given framework, typically a suite of visual development tools and features for developing video games.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Game developers can use game engines to create and publish video games across platforms, such as desktops, mobile devices, video game consoles, and other types of computers.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] The core functionalities commonly covered by a game engine are a 2D or 3D renderer, physics engine, audio engine, scripting, animation, artificial intelligence, networking, streaming, memory management, threads, localization support, scene graph, and cinematics.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Game engine developers often economize game development through reuse or adaptation of abstractions built into game engines for production of various games, or through porting of videogames from a single to other target platforms.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] In many cases, game engines provide a suite of visual development tools in addition to reusable software components.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] These tools are generally provided in an integrated development environment to enable simplified, rapid development of games in a data-driven manner.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Game-engine developers often attempt to preempt implementer needs by developing robust software suites, which include many elements a game developer may need to build a game.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Most game-engine suites provide facilities that ease development, such as graphics, sound, physics and artificial intelligence (AI) functions.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Like other types of middleware, game engines usually provide platform abstraction, allowing the same game to run on various platforms (including game consoles and personal computers) with few, if any, changes made to the game source code.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Often, programmers design game engines with a component-based architecture that allows specific systems in the engine to be replaced or extended with more specialized (and often more expensive) game-middleware components.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Some game engines comprise a series of loosely-connected game middleware components that can be selectively combined to create a custom engine, instead of the more common approach of extending or customizing a flexible integrated product.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] However achieved, extensibility remains a high priority for game engines due to the wide variety of uses for which they are applied.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Despite the specificity of the name "game engine", end users often re-purpose game engines for other kinds of interactive applications with real-time graphical requirements—such as marketing demos, architectural visualizations, training simulations, and modeling environments.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Some game engines only provide real-time 3D rendering capabilities instead of the wide range of functionality needed by games.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] These engines rely upon the game developer to implement the rest of this functionality or to assemble it from other game-middleware components.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] These types of engines are generally referred to as a "graphics engine", "rendering engine", or "3D engine" instead of the all-encompassing term "game engine".
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] This terminology is inconsistently used, as many full-featured 3D game engines are simply referred to as "3D engines".
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Examples of graphics engines include: Crystal Space, Genesis3D, Irrlicht, OGRE, RealmForge, Truevision3D, and Vision Engine.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Modern game- or graphics-engines generally provide a scene graph—an object-oriented representation of the 3D game-world which often simplifies game design and can be used for more efficient rendering of vast virtual worlds.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Most game engines or graphics engines use a Graphics API, which eases communication with the GPU.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] But older games did not have hardware acceleration or GPUs and had to build their own software renderer.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] As technology ages, the components of an engine may become obsolete or insufficient for the requirements of a given project.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Since the complexity of programming an entirely new engine may result in unwanted delays (or necessitate that a project restart from the beginning), an engine-development team may elect to update their existing engine with newer functionality or components.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Game engines are not limited to use in the video game field, and have found uses in other scientific fields.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Part of this is due to game engines being optimized for consumer-grade computing equipment rather than high-performance computing, allowing researchers to develop programs for their use on lower cost machines.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Game engines also simplify many of the computing operations needed for scientific software, including graphics, networking, and interactivity, reducing the need to develop these features themselves.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Before game engines, games were typically written as singular entities: a game for the Atari 2600, for example, had to be designed from the bottom up to make optimal use of the display hardware—this core display routine is now called the kernel by developers of games for older systems.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Other platforms had more leeway, but even when display was not a concern, memory constraints usually sabotaged attempts to create the data-heavy design that an engine needs.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Even on more accommodating platforms, very little could be reused between games.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] The rapid advance of arcade hardware—which was the leading edge of the market at the time—meant that most of the code would have to be thrown out afterwards anyway, as later generations of games would use completely different game designs that took advantage of extra resources.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Thus, most game designs through the 1980s were designed through a hard-coded rule set with a small number of levels and graphics data.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Since the golden age of arcade video games, it became common for video game companies to develop in-house game engines for use with first-party software.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] A notable example of an in-house game engine on home consoles in the mid-1980s was the smooth side-scrolling engine developed by Shigeru Miyamoto's team at Nintendo for the Nintendo Entertainment System (NES).
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] The engine they had developed for the side-scrolling racing game *Excitebike* (1984) was later employed for the scrolling platformer *Super Mario Bros.* (1985).
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] This allowed Mario to smoothly accelerate from a walk to a run, rather than move at a constant speed like in earlier platformers.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] While third-party game engines were not common until the rise of 3D computer graphics in the 1990s, several 2D game creation systems were produced in the 1980s for independent video game development.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Klik & Play (1994) is another legacy offering that is still available.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] The term *game engine* emerged in the mid-1990s, particularly with the rise of 3D games like first-person shooters, which often featured a dedicated first-person shooter engine.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] For instance, Epic Games, founded by Tim Sweeney, debuted its Unreal Engine in 1998.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Later games, such as id Software's *Quake III Arena* and Epic Games' *Unreal* (1998), were designed with this approach in mind, with the engine and content developed separately.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] At the very least, reusable engines make developing game sequels faster and easier, which is a valuable advantage in the competitive video game industry.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] While a strong rivalry existed between Epic Games and id Software around 2000, Epic Game's Unreal Engine has since become far more popular than id Tech 4 and its successor, id Tech 5.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Modern game engines are some of the most complex applications written, often featuring dozens of finely-tuned systems interacting to ensure a precisely-controlled user experience.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] The continued evolution of game engines has created a strong separation between rendering, scripting, artwork, and level design.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] As such, it is now common, for example, for a typical game development team to have several times as many artists as actual programmers.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] While third-party game engines are predominantly used in the development of first-person shooter games, they are also being used across other genres.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] For example, Gamebryo is used in *The Elder Scrolls III: Morrowind* and *Dark Age of Camelot*, whereas Unreal Engine 2 is used in *Lineage II*.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Game engines are also used for games originally developed for home consoles, with RenderWare for the *Grand Theft Auto* and *Burnout* franchises as an example.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Due to modern multi-core systems and growing demands in realism, exploiting threads has become more important.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Separate threads of execution within a game engine manage intensive operations, including rendering, asset streaming, audio playback, and physics simulation.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Racing games have typically been at the forefront of threading with the physics engine running in a separate thread long before other core subsystems were moved, partly because rendering and related tasks need updating at only 30–60 Hz.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] For example, on PlayStation 3, physics ran in *Need For Speed* at 100 Hz, versus *Forza Motorsport 2* at 360 Hz.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Although the term was first used in the 1990s, few earlier systems in 1980s are considered as game engines, such as Sierra's Adventure Game Interpreter (AGI) and SCI systems, LucasArts' SCUMM system and Incentive Software's Freescape engine (in 1986).
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Unlike most modern game engines, these game engines were never used in any third-party products (except for the SCUMM system, which was licensed to and used by Humongous Entertainment).
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] As game engine technology matures and becomes more user friendly, the application of game engines has widened in scope.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] They are now used for serious games: visualization, training, medical, and military simulation applications, with the CryEngine being one example.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] To improve accessibility, new hardware platforms are also now targeted by game engines, including mobile phones (e.g.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Additionally, more game engines are being built upon higher-level languages, such as Java, C# and .NET (e.g., TorqueX, and Visual3D.NET), Python (Panda3D), or Lua Script (Leadwerks).
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] As most 3D-rich games are now mostly limited by the power of a graphics card, the potential slowdown due to translation overheads of higher-level languages becomes negligible, while productivity gains offered by these languages serve the game engine developers' benefit.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] These recent trends are being propelled by companies such as Microsoft to support indie game development.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Microsoft developed XNA as the primary Software Development Kit (SDK) for all video games released on Xbox and their related products.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] This includes the Xbox Live Indie Games channel designed specifically for smaller developers who do not have the extensive resources necessary to box games for sale on retail shelves.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] It is becoming easier and cheaper than ever to develop game engines for platforms that support managed frameworks.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Producers of game engines decide how they allow users to use their products.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Just as gaming is an industry, so are the engines they are built off.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] The major game engines come at varying prices, whether it be in the form of subscription fees or license payments.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Unity and Unreal Engine are currently the two most popular choices for game developers.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Although the differences among the different game engines blur as they build their own tools on top of them, different game developers may be too used to a system to change, or attracted by the huge benefits of such engines regardless of pay-walls.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Free and open-source engines such as Godot, have seen a rise in popularity, particularly following the 2023 Unity pricing controversy which drove game developers and studios to seek engines with a permissive license.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Applied more broadly, game engines themselves can be described as middleware.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] In video games, however, *middleware* is often used to refer to subsystems of functionality within a game engine.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Some game middleware does only one thing, yet does it more convincingly or more efficiently than general purpose middleware.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] The four most-widely used middleware packages that provide subsystems of functionality include RAD Game Tools' Bink, Firelight FMOD, Havok, and Scaleform GFx.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] RAD Game Tools develops Bink for basic video rendering, along with Miles audio, and Granny 3D rendering.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Firelight FMOD is a low cost robust audio library and toolset.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Havok provides a robust physics simulation system, along with a suite of animation and behavior applications.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Scaleform provides GFx for high performance Flash UI and high-quality video playback, and an Input Method Editor (IME) addon for in-game Asian chat support.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Other middleware is used for performance optimization—for example Simplygon helps to optimize and generate level of detail meshes, and Umbra adds occlusion culling optimizations to 3D graphics.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Some middleware contains full source code, or is provided an API reference for a compiled binary library.
[src:unreal-engine/game-engine] Some middleware programs can be licensed either way, usually for a higher fee for full source code.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In a computer graphics context, in standard usage, the word "rendering" by itself means rendering 3D scenes, but it is sometimes used with a broader meaning.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A modifier such as "2D" or "3D" is used when there is potential ambiguity (e.g.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A software application or component that performs rendering is called a **rendering engine**, **render engine**, **rendering system**, **graphics engine**, or simply a **renderer**.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A distinction is made between real-time rendering, in which images are generated and displayed immediately (ideally fast enough to give the impression of motion or animation), and offline rendering (sometimes called pre-rendering) in which images or film frames, are generated for later viewing.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Offline rendering can use a slower and higher-quality renderer.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Interactive applications such as games must primarily use real-time rendering, although they may incorporate pre-rendered content.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rendering produces images of scenes or objects defined using coordinates in 3D space, seen from a particular viewpoint.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] It uses knowledge and ideas from optics, the study of visual perception, mathematics, and software engineering, and it has applications such as video games, simulators, visual effects for films and television, design visualization, and medical diagnosis.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Realistic rendering requires modeling the propagation of light in an environment, e.g. by applying the rendering equation.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Real-time rendering uses high-performance *rasterization* algorithms that process a list of shapes and determine which pixels are covered by each shape.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When more realism is required (e.g. for architectural visualization or visual effects) slower pixel-by-pixel algorithms such as *ray tracing* are used instead.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] (Ray tracing can also be used selectively during rasterized rendering to improve the realism of lighting and reflections.) A type of ray tracing called *path tracing* is currently the most common technique for photorealistic rendering.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Path tracing is also popular for generating high-quality non-photorealistic images, such as frames for 3D animated films.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Both rasterization and ray tracing can be sped up ("accelerated") by specially designed microprocessors called GPUs.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rasterization algorithms are also used to produce images containing only 2D shapes such as polygons and text.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] This type of rendering is sometimes called *2D rendering*, and its applications include digital illustration, graphic design, 2D animation, desktop publishing and the display of user interfaces.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Historically, rendering was called **image synthesis** but today this term is likely to mean AI image generation.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The term "neural rendering" is sometimes used when a neural network is the primary means of generating an image but some degree of control over the output image is provided.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Neural networks can also assist rendering without replacing traditional algorithms, e.g. by removing noise from path traced images.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A large proportion of computer graphics research has worked towards producing images that resemble photographs.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Fundamental techniques that make this possible were invented in the 1980s, but at the end of the decade, photorealism for complex scenes was still considered a distant goal.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Today, photorealism is routinely achievable for offline rendering, but remains difficult for real-time rendering.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In order to produce realistic images, rendering must simulate how light travels from light sources, is reflected, refracted, and scattered (often many times) by objects in the scene, passes through a camera lens, and finally reaches the film or sensor of the camera.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The physics used in these simulations is primarily geometrical optics, in which particles of light follow (usually straight) lines called *rays*, but in some situations (such as when rendering thin films, like the surface of soap bubbles) the wave nature of light must be taken into account.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In realistic scenes, objects are illuminated both by light that arrives directly from a light source (after passing mostly unimpeded through air), and light that has bounced off other objects in the scene.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The simulation of this complex lighting is called global illumination.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In the past, indirect lighting was often faked (especially when rendering animated films) by placing additional hidden lights in the scene, but today path tracing is used to render it accurately.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] For true photorealism, the camera used to take the photograph must be simulated.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The *thin lens approximation* allows combining perspective projection with depth of field (and bokeh) emulation.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Camera lens simulations can be made more realistic by modeling the way light is refracted by the components of the lens.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Motion blur is often simulated if film or video frames are being rendered.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Simulated lens flare and bloom are sometimes added to make the image appear subjectively brighter (although the design of real cameras tries to reduce these effects).
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Realistic rendering uses mathematical descriptions of how different surface materials reflect light, called *reflectance models* or (when physically plausible) *bidirectional reflectance distribution functions (BRDFs)*.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rendering materials such as marble, plant leaves, and human skin requires simulating an effect called subsurface scattering, in which a portion of the light travels into the material, is scattered, and then travels back out again.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The way color, and properties such as roughness, vary over a surface can be represented efficiently using texture mapping.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] For some applications (including early stages of 3D modeling), simplified rendering styles such as wireframe rendering may be appropriate, particularly when the material and surface details have not been defined and only the shape of an object is known.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Games and other real-time applications may use simpler and less realistic rendering techniques as an artistic or design choice, or to allow higher frame rates on lower-end hardware.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Orthographic and isometric projections can be used for a stylized effect or to ensure that parallel lines are depicted as parallel in CAD rendering.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Non-photorealistic rendering (NPR) uses techniques like edge detection and posterization to produce 3D images that resemble technical illustrations, cartoons, or other styles of drawing or painting.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In 2D computer graphics the positions and sizes of shapes are specified using 2D coordinates (x and y) instead of 3D coordinates (x, y, and z).
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering APIs often use a resolution-independent coordinate system, with a viewport determining how to convert coordinates to pixel indexes called *device coordinates*.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Transformations such as scaling, translation, and rotation may be applied before rendering the shapes.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These affine transformations are often represented by 3 × 3 matrices, allowing easier composition of transformations.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Higher-quality 2D rendering engines such as SVG renderers usually implement anti-aliasing to reduce the jagged appearance of rasterized lines and shape edges.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When rendering overlapping shapes, renderers commonly use a "painter's model" in which the shapes are drawn in some determined order, or their contributions to each pixel are composited using blending operations that may depend on the order of the inputs.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Renderers may allow giving shapes a "z index" or "stacking order" to specify the rendering or blending order (unlike the z coordinate used in 3D rendering, this third coordinate only indicates an order, not a distance, and cannot be meaningfully rotated together with the x and y coordinates).
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering typically does not simulate light propagation (which would likely require specifying 3D positions or thickness for the shapes).
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Effects such as drop shadows and transparency are defined by mathematical functions with no physical basis.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering for print output may need to support very high resolutions, e.g.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 600 or 1200 DPI for a typical laser printer, or 2400 DPI or higher for an imagesetter or platesetter.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Grayscale and color images require halftones (or some form of dithering or stochastic screening) and color separations.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A rendering engine called a *raster image processor* (RIP) converts input data such as PDF files into the high-resolution bitmap images used by the printer.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Before a 3D scene or 2D image can be rendered, it must be described in a way that the rendering software can understand.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Historically, inputs for both 2D and 3D rendering were usually text files, which are easier than binary files for humans to edit and debug.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Traditional rendering algorithms use geometric descriptions of 3D scenes or 2D images.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Applications and algorithms that render visualizations of data scanned from the real world, or scientific simulations, may require different types of input data.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The PostScript format (which is often credited with the rise of desktop publishing) provides a standardized, interoperable way to describe 2D graphics and page layout.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The Scalable Vector Graphics (SVG) format is also text-based, and the PDF format uses the PostScript language internally.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Many file formats exist for storing individual 3D objects or "models".
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These can be imported into a larger scene, or loaded on-demand by rendering software or games.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A realistic scene may require hundreds of items like household objects, vehicles, and trees, and 3D artists often utilize large libraries of models.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In game production, these models (along with other data such as textures, audio files, and animations) are referred to as "assets".
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Scientific and engineering visualization often requires rendering volumetric data generated by 3D scans or simulations.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Perhaps the most common source of such data is medical CT and MRI scans, which need to be rendered for diagnosis.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Volumetric data can be extremely large, and requires specialized data formats to store it efficiently, particularly if the volume is *sparse* (with empty regions that do not contain data).
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Before rendering, level sets for volumetric data can be extracted and converted into a mesh of triangles, e.g. by using the marching cubes algorithm.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Algorithms have also been developed that work directly with volumetric data, for example to render realistic depictions of the way light is scattered and absorbed by clouds and smoke, and this type of volumetric rendering is used extensively in visual effects for movies.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When rendering lower-resolution volumetric data without interpolation, the individual cubes or "voxels" may be visible, an effect sometimes used deliberately for game graphics.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Photographs of real world objects can be incorporated into a rendered scene by using them as textures for 3D objects.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Photos of a scene can also be stitched together to create panoramic images or environment maps, which allow the scene to be rendered very efficiently but only from a single viewpoint.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Scanning of real objects and scenes using structured light or lidar produces point clouds consisting of the coordinates of millions of individual points in space, sometimes along with color information.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These point clouds may either be rendered directly or converted into meshes before rendering.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A more recent, experimental approach is description of scenes using radiance fields which define the color, intensity, and direction of incoming light at each point in space.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] (This is conceptually similar to, but not identical to, the light field recorded by a hologram.) For any useful resolution, the amount of data in a radiance field is so large that it is impractical to represent it directly as volumetric data, and an approximation function must be found.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Neural networks are typically used to generate and evaluate these approximations, sometimes using video frames, or a collection of photographs of a scene taken at different angles, as "training data".
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Algorithms related to neural networks have recently been used to find approximations of a scene as 3D Gaussians.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The resulting representation is similar to a point cloud, except that it uses fuzzy, partially-transparent blobs of varying dimensions and orientations instead of points.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] As with neural radiance fields, these approximations are often generated from photographs or video frames.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The output of rendering may be displayed immediately on the screen (many times a second, in the case of real-time rendering such as games) or saved in a raster graphics file format such as JPEG or PNG.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] High-end rendering applications commonly use the OpenEXR file format, which can represent finer gradations of colors and high dynamic range lighting, allowing tone mapping or other adjustments to be applied afterwards without loss of quality.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The output of a renderer sometimes includes more than just RGB color values.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Transparency information can be included, allowing rendered foreground objects to be composited with photographs or video.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] It is also sometimes useful to store the contributions of different lights, or of specular and diffuse lighting, as separate channels, so lighting can be adjusted after rendering.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The OpenEXR format allows storing many channels of data in a single file.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Renderers such as Blender and Pixar RenderMan support a large variety of configurable values called Arbitrary Output Variables (AOVs).
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Choosing how to render a 3D scene usually involves trade-offs between speed, memory usage, and realism (although realism is not always desired).
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The **algorithms** developed over the years follow a loose progression, with more advanced methods becoming practical as computing power and memory capacity increased.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Multiple techniques may be used for a single final image.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important distinction is between image order algorithms, which iterate over pixels in the image, and object order algorithms, which iterate over objects in the scene.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For simple scenes, object order is usually more efficient, as there are fewer objects than pixels.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] algorithms that also support filled shapes.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In principle, any 2D vector graphics renderer can be used to render 3D objects by first projecting them onto a 2D image plane.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Different realistic or stylized effects can be obtained by coloring the pixels covered by the objects in different ways.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rasterization is usually synonymous with "object order" rendering (as described above).
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It can be used to implement "image order" rendering by casting a ray for each pixel, and finding a corresponding point in the scene.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] , requiring a varying number of ray casting operations for each path.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] is usually in the domain of path tracing.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] approach that breaks surfaces in the scene into pieces, and estimates the amount of light that each piece receives from light sources, or indirectly from other surfaces.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] of each surface is known, the scene can be rendered using rasterization or ray tracing.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] , giving ray tracing a rigorous mathematical foundation.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Each of the above approaches has many variations, and there is some overlap.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Path tracing may be considered either a distinct technique or a particular type of ray tracing.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Note that the usage of terminology related to ray tracing and path tracing has changed significantly over time.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray marching is a family of algorithms, used by ray casting, for finding intersections between a ray and a complex object, such as a volumetric dataset or a surface defined by a signed distance function.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It is not, by itself, a rendering method, but it can be incorporated into ray tracing and path tracing, and is used by rasterization to implement screen-space reflection and other effects.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A technique called photon mapping traces paths of photons from a light source to an object, accumulating data about irradiance which is then used during conventional ray tracing or path tracing.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering a scene using only rays traced from the light source to the camera is impractical, even though it corresponds more closely to reality, because a huge number of photons would need to be simulated, only a tiny fraction of which actually hit the camera.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Some authors call conventional ray tracing "backward" ray tracing because it traces the paths of photons backwards from the camera to the light source, and call following paths from the light source (as in photon mapping) "forward" ray tracing.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However, sometimes the meaning of these terms is reversed.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Tracing rays starting at the light source can also be called *particle tracing* or *light tracing*, which avoids this ambiguity.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Real-time rendering, including video game graphics, typically uses rasterization, but increasingly combines it with ray tracing and path tracing.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] To enable realistic global illumination, real-time rendering often relies on pre-rendered ("baked") lighting for stationary objects.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For moving objects, it may use a technique called *light probes*, in which lighting is recorded by rendering omnidirectional views of the scene at chosen points in space (often points on a grid to allow easier interpolation).
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These are similar to environment maps, but typically use a very low resolution or an approximation such as spherical harmonics.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The term *rasterization* (in a broad sense) encompasses many techniques used for 2D rendering and real-time 3D rendering.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] 3D animated films were rendered by rasterization before ray tracing and path tracing became practical.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A renderer combines rasterization with *geometry processing* (which is not specific to rasterization) and *pixel processing* which computes the RGB color values to be placed in the *framebuffer* for display.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Historically, 3D rasterization used algorithms like the *Warnock algorithm* and *scanline rendering* (also called "scan-conversion"), which can handle arbitrary polygons and can rasterize many shapes simultaneously.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Although such algorithms are still important for 2D rendering, 3D rendering now usually divides shapes into triangles and rasterizes them individually using simpler methods.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] High-performance algorithms exist for rasterizing 2D lines, including anti-aliased lines, as well as ellipses and filled triangles.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important special case of 2D rasterization is text rendering, which requires careful anti-aliasing and rounding of coordinates to avoid distorting the letterforms and preserve spacing, density, and sharpness.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] After 3D coordinates have been projected onto the image plane, rasterization is primarily a 2D problem, but the 3rd dimension necessitates *hidden surface removal*.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early computer graphics used geometric algorithms or ray casting to remove the hidden portions of shapes, or used the *painter's algorithm*, which sorts shapes by depth (distance from camera) and renders them from back to front.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Depth sorting was later avoided by incorporating depth comparison into the scanline rendering algorithm.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The *z-buffer* algorithm performs the comparisons indirectly by including a depth or "z" value in the framebuffer.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A pixel is only covered by a shape if that shape's z value is lower (indicating closer to the camera) than the z value currently in the buffer.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The z-buffer requires additional memory (an expensive resource at the time it was invented) but simplifies the rasterization code and permits multiple passes.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Memory is now faster and more plentiful, and a z-buffer is almost always used for real-time rendering.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A drawback of the basic z-buffer algorithm is that each pixel ends up either entirely covered by a single object or filled with the background color, causing jagged edges in the final image.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early *anti-aliasing* approaches addressed this by detecting when a pixel is partially covered by a shape, and calculating the covered area.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The A-buffer (and other supersampling and multi-sampling techniques) solve the problem less precisely but with higher performance.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For real-time 3D graphics, it has become common to use complicated heuristics (and even neural-networks) to perform anti-aliasing.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In 3D rasterization, color is usually determined by a *pixel shader* or *fragment shader*, a small program that is run for each pixel.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Until relatively recently, Pixar used rasterization for rendering its animated films.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Unlike the renderers commonly used for real-time graphics, the Reyes rendering system in Pixar's RenderMan software was optimized for rendering very small (pixel-sized) polygons, and incorporated stochastic sampling techniques more typically associated with ray tracing.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] One of the simplest ways to render a 3D scene is to test if a ray starting at the viewpoint (the "eye" or "camera") intersects any of the geometric shapes in the scene, repeating this test using a different ray direction for each pixel.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This method, called *ray casting*, was important in early computer graphics, and is a fundamental building block for more advanced algorithms.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray casting can be used to render shapes defined by *constructive solid geometry* (CSG) operations.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early ray casting experiments include the work of Arthur Appel in the 1960s.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Appel rendered shadows by casting an additional ray from each visible surface point towards a light source.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] He also tried rendering the density of illumination by casting random rays from the light source towards the object and plotting the intersection points (similar to the later technique called *photon mapping*).
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When rendering scenes containing many objects, testing the intersection of a ray with every object becomes very expensive.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Special data structures are used to speed up this process by allowing large numbers of objects to be excluded quickly (such as objects behind the camera).
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These structures are analogous to database indexes for finding the relevant objects.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The most common are the *bounding volume hierarchy* (BVH), which stores a pre-computed bounding box or sphere for each branch of a tree of objects, and the *k-d tree* which recursively divides space into two parts.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent GPUs include hardware acceleration for BVH intersection tests.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] K-d trees are a special case of *binary space partitioning*, which was frequently used in early computer graphics (it can also generate a rasterization order for the painter's algorithm).
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Octrees*, another historically popular technique, are still often used for volumetric data.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Geometric formulas are sufficient for finding the intersection of a ray with shapes like spheres, polygons, and polyhedra, but for most curved surfaces there is no analytic solution, or the intersection is difficult to compute accurately using limited precision floating point numbers.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Root-finding algorithms such as Newton's method can sometimes be used.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] To avoid these complications, curved surfaces are often approximated as meshes of triangles.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Volume rendering (e.g. rendering clouds and smoke), and some surfaces such as fractals, may require ray marching instead of basic ray casting.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray casting can be used to render an image by tracing light rays backwards from a simulated camera.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] After finding a point on a surface where a ray originated, another ray is traced towards the light source to determine if anything is casting a shadow on that point.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If there are multiple light sources, brightness contributions of the lights are added together.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For color images, calculations are repeated for multiple wavelengths of light (e.g. red, green, and blue).
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing usually performs anti-aliasing by taking the average of multiple samples for each pixel.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It may also use multiple samples for effects like depth of field and motion blur.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If evenly spaced ray directions or times are used for each of these features, many rays are required, and some aliasing will remain.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Cook-style*, *stochastic*, or *Monte Carlo ray tracing* avoids this problem by using random sampling instead of evenly spaced samples.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This type of ray tracing is commonly called *distributed ray tracing*, or *distribution ray tracing* because it samples rays from probability distributions.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Distribution ray tracing can also render realistic "soft" shadows from large lights by using a random sample of points on the light when testing for shadowing, and it can simulate chromatic aberration by sampling multiple wavelengths from the spectrum of light.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Real surface materials reflect small amounts of light in almost every direction because they have small (or microscopic) bumps and grooves.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A distribution ray tracer can simulate this by sampling possible ray directions, which allows rendering blurry reflections from glossy and metallic surfaces.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However, if this procedure is repeated recursively to simulate realistic indirect lighting, and if more than one sample is taken at each surface point, the tree of rays quickly becomes huge.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Another kind of ray tracing, called *path tracing*, handles indirect light more efficiently, avoiding branching, and ensures that the distribution of all possible paths from a light source to the camera is sampled in an unbiased way.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing was often used for rendering reflections in animated films, until path tracing became standard for film rendering.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Films such as Shrek 2 and Monsters University also used distribution ray tracing or path tracing to precompute indirect illumination for a scene or frame prior to rendering it using rasterization.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Advances in GPU technology have made real-time ray tracing possible in games, although it is currently almost always used in combination with rasterization.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This enables visual effects that are difficult with only rasterization, including reflection from curved surfaces and interreflective objects, and shadows that are accurate over a wide range of distances and surface orientations.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing support is included in recent versions of the graphics APIs used by games, such as DirectX, Metal, and Vulkan.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing has been used to render simulated black holes, and the appearance of objects moving at close to the speed of light, by taking spacetime curvature and relativistic effects into account during light ray simulation.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Radiosity (named after the radiometric quantity of the same name) is a method for rendering objects illuminated by light bouncing off rough or matte surfaces.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This type of illumination is called *indirect light*, *environment lighting*, *diffuse lighting*, or *diffuse interreflection*, and the problem of rendering it realistically is called *global illumination*.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rasterization and basic forms of ray tracing (other than distribution ray tracing and path tracing) can only roughly approximate indirect light, e.g. by adding a uniform "ambient" lighting amount chosen by the artist.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Radiosity techniques are also suited to rendering scenes with *area lights* such as rectangular fluorescent lighting panels, which are difficult for rasterization and traditional ray tracing.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In the original radiosity method (first proposed in 1984) now called *classical radiosity*, surfaces and lights in the scene are split into pieces called *patches*, a process called *meshing* (this step makes it a finite element method).
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The rendering code must then determine what fraction of the light being emitted or diffusely reflected (scattered) by each patch is received by each other patch.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These fractions are called *form factors* or *view factors* (first used in engineering to model radiative heat transfer).
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The form factors are multiplied by the albedo of the receiving surface and put in a matrix.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The lighting in the scene can then be expressed as a matrix equation (or equivalently a system of linear equations) that can be solved by methods from linear algebra.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Solving the radiosity equation gives the total amount of light emitted and reflected by each patch, which is divided by area to get a value called *radiosity* that can be used when rasterizing or ray tracing to determine the color of pixels corresponding to visible parts of the patch.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For real-time rendering, this value (or more commonly the irradiance, which does not depend on local surface albedo) can be pre-computed and stored in a texture (called an *irradiance map*) or stored as vertex data for 3D models.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This feature was used in architectural visualization software to allow real-time walk-throughs of a building interior after computing the lighting.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The large size of the matrices used in classical radiosity (the square of the number of patches) causes problems for realistic scenes.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Practical implementations may use Jacobi or Gauss-Seidel iterations, which is equivalent (at least in the Jacobi case) to simulating the propagation of light one bounce at a time until the amount of light remaining (not yet absorbed by surfaces) is insignificant.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Form factors may be recomputed when they are needed, to avoid storing a complete matrix in memory.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The quality of rendering is often determined by the size of the patches, e.g. very fine meshes are needed to depict the edges of shadows accurately.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important improvement is *hierarchical radiosity*, which uses a coarser mesh (larger patches) for simulating the transfer of light between surfaces that are far away from one another, and adaptively sub-divides the patches as needed.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This allows radiosity to be used for much larger and more complex scenes.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Alternative and extended versions of the radiosity method support non-Lambertian surfaces, such as glossy surfaces and mirrors, and sometimes use volumes or "clusters" of objects as well as surface patches.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Simplified and partially precomputed versions of radiosity are widely used for real-time rendering, combined with techniques such as *octree radiosity* that store approximations of the light field.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As part of the approach known as *physically based rendering*, **path tracing** has become the dominant technique for rendering realistic scenes, including effects for movies.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For example, the popular open source 3D software Blender uses path tracing in its Cycles renderer.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Like *distributed ray tracing*, path tracing is a kind of *stochastic* or *randomized* ray tracing that uses Monte Carlo or Quasi-Monte Carlo integration.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It was proposed and named in 1986 by Jim Kajiya in the same paper as the rendering equation.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Kajiya suggested reducing the noise present in the output images by using *stratified sampling* and *importance sampling* for making random decisions such as choosing which ray to follow at each step of a path.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Even with these techniques, path tracing would not have been practical for film rendering, using computers available at the time, because the computational cost of generating enough samples to reduce variance to an acceptable level was too high.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Monster House, the first feature film rendered entirely using path tracing, was not released until 20 years later.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In its basic form, path tracing is inefficient (requiring too many samples) for rendering caustics and scenes where light enters indirectly through narrow spaces.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Attempts were made to address these weaknesses in the 1990s.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Metropolis light transport* samples paths by modifying paths that were previously traced, spending more time exploring paths that are similar to other "bright" paths, which increases the chance of discovering even brighter paths.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Multiple importance sampling* provides a way to reduce variance when combining samples from more than one sampling method, particularly when some samples are much noisier than the others.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This later work was summarized and expanded upon in Eric Veach's 1997 PhD thesis, which helped raise interest in path tracing in the computer graphics community.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The Arnold renderer, first released in 1998, proved that path tracing was practical for rendering frames for films, and that there was a demand for unbiased and physically based rendering in the film industry; other commercial and open source path tracing renderers began appearing.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Computational cost was addressed by rapid advances in CPU and cluster performance.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Path tracing's relative simplicity and its nature as a Monte Carlo method (sampling hundreds or thousands of paths per pixel) have made it attractive to implement on a GPU, especially on recent GPUs that support ray tracing acceleration technology such as Nvidia's RTX and OptiX.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However bidirectional path tracing and Metropolis light transport are more difficult to implement efficiently on a GPU.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Techniques have been developed to denoise the output of path tracing, reducing the number of paths required to achieve acceptable quality, at the risk of losing some detail or introducing small-scale artifacts that are more objectionable than noise.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural networks are now widely used for this purpose.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Research into improving path tracing continues.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Many variations of bidirectional path tracing and Metropolis light transport have been explored, and ways of combining path tracing with photon mapping.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent *path guiding* approaches construct approximations of the light field probability distribution in each volume of space, so paths can be sampled more effectively.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] By combining denoising and hardware ray tracing acceleration, it is now practical to use path tracing for real-time rendering.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Due to performance constraints, biased techniques such as a radiance cache may be incorporated.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Spatiotemporal reservoir resampling (ReSTIR) aims to improve the quality of real-time path tracing and allow more complex lighting by reusing samples (paths) from previous frames and adjacent pixels.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As of 2003, machine learning (ML) techniques were being used in other areas of computer graphics, such as texture synthesis, fitting surfaces to point clouds, and fitting curves to motion capture data.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The use of ML for rendering expanded with the availability of GPUs that can evaluate neural networks (especially convolutional neural networks) quickly.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural networks and Gaussian mixture models have been used in conjunction with rendering techniques such as path tracing to encode bidirectional reflectance distribution functions (BRDFs), or to encode cached radiance at points in space (for biased acceleration of rendering or for path guiding).
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural radiance fields (NeRFs) take the latter approach to an extreme, encoding radiance at all points in a volume, and using evaluation of this approximation as the primary rendering method.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] One of the most widely used applications of machine learning in rendering is denoising of path traced images (in practice, most path tracing now likely uses such a denoiser).
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Denoisers specialized for real-time rendering can work with very low sample counts and improve temporal coherence to reduce flickering.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering is usually limited by available computing power and memory bandwidth, and so specialized hardware has been developed to speed it up ("accelerate" it), particularly for real-time rendering.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Hardware features such as a framebuffer for raster graphics are required to display the output of rendering smoothly in real time.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Hardware acceleration does not replace the use of software for rendering, rather it speeds up selected operations or calculations using dedicated circuits, or runs portions of the software's code on a different type of processor.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In the era of vector monitors (also called *calligraphic displays*), a display processing unit (DPU) was a dedicated CPU or coprocessor that maintained a list of visual elements and redrew them continuously on the screen by controlling an electron beam.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Advanced DPUs such as Evans & Sutherland's Line Drawing System-1 (and later models produced into the 1980s) incorporated 3D coordinate transformation features to accelerate rendering of wire-frame images.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Evans & Sutherland also made the Digistar planetarium projection system, which was a vector display that could render both stars and wire-frame graphics (the vector-based Digistar and Digistar II were used in many planetariums, and a few may still be in operation).
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A Digistar prototype was used for rendering 3D star fields for the film Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan – some of the first 3D computer graphics sequences ever seen in a feature film.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Shaded 3D graphics rendering in the 1970s and early 1980s was usually implemented on general-purpose computers, such as the PDP-10 used by researchers at the University of Utah.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It was difficult to speed up using specialized hardware because it involves a pipeline of complex steps, requiring data addressing, decision-making, and computation capabilities typically only provided by CPUs (although dedicated circuits for speeding up particular operations were proposed ).
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Supercomputers or specially designed multi-CPU computers or clusters were sometimes used for ray tracing.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Clark and Marc Hannah designed the Geometry Engine, a VLSI chip for performing some of the steps of the 3D rasterization pipeline, and started the company Silicon Graphics (SGI) to commercialize this technology.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Home computers and game consoles in the 1980s contained graphics coprocessors that were capable of scrolling and filling areas of the display, and drawing sprites and lines, though they were not useful for rendering realistic images.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Towards the end of the 1980s PC graphics cards and arcade games with 3D rendering acceleration began to appear, and in the 1990s such technology became commonplace.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Today, even low-power mobile processors typically incorporate 3D graphics acceleration features.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The 3D graphics accelerators of the 1990s evolved into modern GPUs.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] GPUs are general-purpose processors, like CPUs, but they are designed for tasks that can be broken into many small, similar, mostly independent sub-tasks (such as rendering individual pixels) and performed in parallel.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Due to their origins, GPUs typically still provide specialized hardware acceleration for some steps of a traditional 3D rasterization pipeline, including hidden surface removal using a z-buffer, and texture mapping with mipmaps, but these features are no longer always used.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent GPUs have features to accelerate finding the intersections of rays with a bounding volume hierarchy, to help speed up all variants of ray tracing and path tracing, as well as neural network acceleration features sometimes useful for rendering.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering algorithms will run efficiently on a GPU only if they can be implemented using small groups of threads that perform mostly the same operations.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As an example of code that meets this requirement: when rendering a small square of pixels in a simple ray-traced image, all threads will likely be intersecting rays with the same object and performing the same lighting computations.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For performance and architectural reasons, GPUs run groups of around 16-64 threads called *warps* or *wavefronts* in lock-step (all threads in the group are executing the same instructions at the same time).
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If not all threads in the group need to run particular blocks of code (due to conditions) then some threads will be idle, or the results of their computations will be discarded, causing degraded performance.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Historically, the term *hardware rendering* (possibly an abbreviation of "hardware accelerated rendering" or "hardware-assisted rendering") was sometimes used to mean rendering using a hardware-accelerated rasterization pipeline (typically for real-time rendering).
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In contrast, *software rendering* meant offline rendering using software that was not limited by the capabilities of graphics hardware, and could use more realistic and higher quality techniques.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Both hardware and software have evolved, and although these terms are still used, their meaning may now be context-dependent.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When OpenGL and Direct3D were introduced in the 1990s, there was a need to use these APIs on computers that did not have hardware acceleration for 3D graphics.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] "Fallback" rendering implementations were provided that did not require special hardware, and these are sometimes called "software renderers" (today hardware acceleration is almost always available, and these CPU-only implementations are used primarily for testing).
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] More recently, "software rendering" may also mean rendering that does not use graphics APIs such as OpenGL, Metal, Direct3D, or Vulkan.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Types of renderers that in the past might have been called "software renderers" (e.g. path tracing renderers used for offline rendering for movies) now commonly use GPU acceleration, often via APIs such as CUDA or OpenCL, which are not graphics-specific.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Since these latter APIs allow running C++ code on a GPU, it is now possible to run the same rendering code on either a CPU or GPU.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The following is a rough timeline of frequently mentioned rendering techniques, including areas of current research.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Note that even in cases where an idea was named in a specific paper, there were almost always multiple researchers or teams working in the same area (including earlier related work).
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When a method is first proposed it is often very inefficient, and it takes additional research and practical efforts to turn it into a useful technique.
[src:unreal-engine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The list focuses on academic research and does not include hardware.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] A **scene graph** is a hierarchical data structure commonly used by vector-based graphics editing applications and modern computer games, which cascades the inheritance or spatial representation of a set of objects.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] It is a collection of nodes in a graph or tree structure.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] A tree node may have many children but only a single parent, with the effect of a parent applied to all its child nodes; an operation performed on a group automatically propagates its effect to all of its members.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] In many programs, associating a geometrical transformation matrix (see also transformation and matrix) at each group level and concatenating such matrices together is an efficient and natural way to process such operations.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] A common feature, for instance, is the ability to group related shapes and objects into a compound object that can then be manipulated as easily as a single object.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] In vector-based graphics editing, each leaf node in a scene graph represents some atomic unit of the document, usually a shape such as an ellipse or Bezier path.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] Although shapes themselves (particularly paths) can be decomposed further into nodes such as spline nodes, it is practical to think of the scene graph as composed of shapes rather than going to a lower level of representation.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] Another useful and user-driven node concept is the layer.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] A layer acts like a transparent sheet upon which any number of shapes and shape groups can be placed.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] The document then becomes a set of layers, any of which can be conveniently made invisible, dimmed, or locked (made read-only).
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] Some applications place all layers in a linear list, while others support layers within layers to any desired depth.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] Internally, there may be no real structural difference between layers and groups at all, since they are both just nodes of a scene graph.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] If differences are needed, a common type declaration in C++ would be to make a generic node class, and then derive layers and groups as subclasses.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] A visibility member, for example, would be a feature of a layer, but not necessarily of a group.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] Scene graphs are useful for modern games using 3D graphics and increasingly large worlds or levels.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] In such applications, nodes in a scene graph (generally) represent entities or objects in the scene.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] For instance, a game might define a logical relationship between a knight and a horse so that the knight is considered an extension to the horse.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] The scene graph would have a 'horse' node with a 'knight' node attached to it.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] The scene graph may also describe the spatial, as well as the logical, relationship of the various entities: the knight moves through 3D space as the horse moves.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] In these large applications, memory requirements are major considerations when designing a scene graph.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] For this reason, many large scene graph systems use geometry instancing to reduce memory costs and increase speed.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] In our example above, each knight is a separate scene node, but the graphical representation of the knight (made up of a 3D mesh, textures, materials and shaders) is instanced.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] This means that only a single copy of the data is kept, which is then referenced by any 'knight' nodes in the scene graph.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] This allows a reduced memory budget and increased speed, since when a new knight node is created, the appearance data need not be duplicated.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] The simplest form of scene graph uses an array or linked list data structure, and displaying its shapes is simply a matter of linearly iterating the nodes one by one.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] Other common operations, such as checking to see which shape intersects the mouse pointer are also done via linear searches.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] For small scene graphs, this tends to suffice.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] Applying an operation on a scene graph requires some way of dispatching an operation based on a node's type.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] For example, in a render operation, a transformation group node would accumulate its transformation by matrix multiplication, vector displacement, quaternions or Euler angles.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] After which a leaf node sends the object off for rendering to the renderer.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] Some implementations might render the object directly, which invokes the underlying rendering API, such as DirectX or OpenGL.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] But since the underlying implementation of the rendering API usually lacks portability, one might separate the scene graph and rendering systems instead.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] In order to accomplish this type of dispatching, several different approaches can be taken.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] In object-oriented languages such as C++, this can easily be achieved by virtual functions, where each represents an operation that can be performed on a node.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] Virtual functions are simple to write, but it is usually impossible to add new operations to nodes without access to the source code.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] Alternatively, the *visitor pattern* can be used.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] This has a similar disadvantage in that it is similarly difficult to add new node types.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] Other techniques involve the use of RTTI (Run-Time Type Information).
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] The operation can be realised as a class that is passed to the current node; it then queries the node's type using RTTI and looks up the correct operation in an array of callbacks or functors.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] This requires that the map of types to callbacks or functors be initialized at runtime, but offers more flexibility, speed and extensibility.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] Variations on these techniques exist, and new methods can offer added benefits.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] One alternative is scene graph rebuilding, where the scene graph is rebuilt for each of the operations performed.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] This, however, can be very slow, but produces a highly optimised scene graph.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] It demonstrates that a good scene graph implementation depends heavily on the application in which it is used.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] Traversals are the key to the power of applying operations to scene graphs.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] At this point, many scene graph engines then traverse back up the tree, applying a similar operation.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] For example, consider a render operation that takes transformations into account: while recursively traversing down the scene graph hierarchy, a pre-render operation is called.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] If the node is a transformation node, it adds its own transformation to the current transformation matrix.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] Once the operation finishes traversing all the children of a node, it calls the node's post-render operation so that the transformation node can undo the transformation.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] This approach drastically reduces the necessary amount of matrix multiplication.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] Some scene graph operations are actually more efficient when nodes are traversed in a different order – this is where some systems implement scene graph rebuilding to reorder the scene graph into an easier-to-parse format or tree.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] For example, in 2D cases, scene graphs typically render themselves by starting at the tree's root node and then recursively draw the child nodes.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] The tree's leaves represent the most foreground objects.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] Since drawing proceeds from back to front with closer objects simply overwriting farther ones, the process is known as employing the Painter's algorithm.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] In 3D systems, which often employ depth buffers, it is more efficient to draw the closest objects first, since farther objects often need only be depth-tested instead of actually rendered, because they are occluded by nearer objects.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] Bounding Volume Hierarchies (BVHs) are useful for numerous tasks – including efficient culling and speeding up collision detection between objects.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] A BVH is a spatial structure, but doesn't have to partition the geometry (see spatial partitioning below).
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] A BVH is a tree of bounding volumes (often spheres, axis-aligned bounding boxes or oriented bounding boxes).
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] At the bottom of the hierarchy, the size of the volume is just large enough to encompass a single object tightly (or possibly even some smaller fraction of an object in high resolution BVHs).
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] As one ascends the hierarchy, each node has its own volume that tightly encompasses all the volumes beneath it.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] At the root of the tree is a volume that encompasses all the volumes in the tree (the whole scene).
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] BVHs are useful for speeding up collision detection between objects.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] If an object's bounding volume does not intersect a volume higher in the tree, it cannot intersect any object below that node (so they are all rejected very quickly).
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] There are some similarities between BVHs and scene graphs.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] A scene graph can easily be adapted to include/become a BVH – if each node has a volume associated or there is a purpose-built "bound node" added in at convenient location in the hierarchy.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] This may not be the typical view of a scene graph, but there are benefits to including a BVH in a scene graph.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] An effective way of combining spatial partitioning and scene graphs is by creating a scene leaf node that contains the spatial partitioning data.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] This can increase computational efficiency of rendering.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] Spatial data is usually static and generally contains non-moving scene data in some partitioned form.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] Some systems may have the systems and their rendering separately.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] This is fine and there are no real advantages to either method.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] In particular, it is bad to have the scene graph contained within the spatial partitioning system, as the scene graph is better thought of as the grander system to the spatial partitioning.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] Very large drawings, or scene graphs that are generated solely at runtime (as happens in ray tracing rendering programs), require defining of group nodes in a more automated fashion.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] A raytracer, for example, will take a scene description of a 3D model and build an internal representation that breaks up its individual parts into bounding boxes (also called bounding slabs).
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] These boxes are grouped hierarchically so that ray intersection tests (as part of visibility determination) can be efficiently computed.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] A group box that does not intersect an eye ray, for example, can entirely skip testing any of its members.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] A similar efficiency holds in 2D applications as well.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] If the user has magnified a document so that only part of it is visible on their computer screen, and then scrolls in it, it is useful to use a bounding box (or in this case, a bounding rectangle scheme) to quickly determine which scene graph elements are visible and thus actually need to be drawn.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] Depending on the particulars of the application's drawing performance, a large part of the scene graph's design can be impacted by rendering efficiency considerations.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] In 3D video games such as Quake, binary space partitioning (BSP) trees are heavily favored to minimize visibility tests.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] BSP trees, however, take a very long time to compute from design scene graphs, and must be recomputed if the design scene graph changes, so the levels tend to remain static, and dynamic characters aren't generally considered in the spatial partitioning scheme.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] Scene graphs for dense regular objects such as heightfields and polygon meshes tend to employ quadtrees and octrees, which are specialized variants of a 3D bounding box hierarchy.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] Since a heightfield occupies a box volume itself, recursively subdividing this box into eight subboxes (hence the 'oct' in octree) until individual heightfield elements are reached is efficient and natural.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] PHIGS was the first commercial scene graph specification, and became an ANSI standard in 1988.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] Disparate implementations were provided by Unix hardware vendors.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] The HOOPS 3D Graphics System appears to have been the first commercial scene graph library provided by a single software vendor.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] It was designed to run on disparate lower-level 2D and 3D interfaces, with the first major production version (v3.0) completed in 1991.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] Silicon Graphics (SGI) released OpenGL Performer or more commonly called Performer in 1991 which was the primary scenegraph system for most SGI products into the future.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] IRIS Inventor 1.0 (1992) was released by SGI, which was a high level scene graph built on top of Performer.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] It was followed up with Open Inventor in 1994, another iteration of the high level scene graph built on top of newer releases of Performer.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] More 3D scene graph libraries can be found in Category:3D scenegraph APIs.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] X3D is a royalty-free open standards file format and run-time architecture to represent and communicate 3D scenes and objects using XML.
[src:unreal-engine/scene-graph] It is an ISO-ratified standard that provides a system for the storage, retrieval and playback of real-time graphics content embedded in applications, all within an open architecture to support a wide array of domains and user scenarios.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] The latest generation, Unreal Engine 5, was launched in April 2022.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Its source code is available on GitHub, and commercial use is granted based on a royalty model, with Epic charging 5% of revenues over US $1 million, which is waived for games published exclusively on the Epic Games Store.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Epic has incorporated features in the engine from acquired companies such as Quixel.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Unreal Engine 1 was initially developed in 1995 by Epic Games founder Tim Sweeney for *Unreal* and used either software rendering or hardware rendering via support for various early 3D accelerators like the 3DFX Voodoo Graphics via the 3DFX Glide API.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] It supported Windows, Linux, Mac and Unix.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Epic later began to license the Engine to other game studios.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Unreal Engine 2 transitioned the engine from software rendering to hardware rendering and brought support for the PlayStation 2, Xbox, and GameCube consoles.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] The first game using UE2 was released in 2002 and its last update was shipped in 2005.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Unreal Engine 3 was one of the first game engines to support multithreading.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] It used DirectX 9 as its baseline graphics API, simplifying its rendering code.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] The first games using UE3 were released at the end of 2006.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Unreal Engine 4 brought support for physically based materials and the "Blueprints" visual scripting system.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] The first game using UE4 was released in April 2014.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] It was the first version of Unreal to be free to download with royalty payments on game revenue.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Unreal Engine 5 features Nanite, a virtualized geometry system that allows game developers to use arbitrarily high quality meshes with automatically generated Level of Detail, and Lumen, a dynamic global illumination and reflections system that uses software and hardware ray tracing.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] It was revealed in May 2020 and officially released in April 2022.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Epic Games chief executive Tim Sweeney first publicly discussed the development of Unreal Engine 6 in 2024.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] In an interview with *The Verge*, Sweeney stated that the company was working towards a new version of the engine that would merge Epic Games' development tools with the systems built for Unreal Editor for *Fortnite*.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Sweeney discussed Unreal Engine 6 on the Lex Fridman podcast in 2025, and indicated that the first preview builds would be available in two to three years.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] The next version will aim to unify the currently separate development streams used for *Fortnite* and the broader engine.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Epic Games officially announced Unreal Engine 6 on May 24, 2026, during the Rocket League Championship Series (RLCS) Paris Major.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Alongside the announcement, Epic confirmed that *Rocket League* would become the first announced title to transition to Unreal Engine 6, replacing its long-running Unreal Engine 3 foundation.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] In the State of Unreal 2026, more details were confirmed about UE6.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Epic confirmed that Blueprints and Actors would eventually be replaced by Verse and Scene Graph (although they will be retained in the early versions of UE6), and that new technology will allow for more than 100 players to be in the same match at a time.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] They also confirmed an early access release date of "Late 2027-ish," with a full release around 12-18 months later.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] UnrealScript (often abbreviated to UScript) was Unreal Engine's native scripting language used for authoring game code and gameplay events before the release of Unreal Engine 4.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] The language was designed for simple, high-level game programming.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] UnrealScript was programmed by Tim Sweeney, who also created an earlier game scripting language, ZZT-OOP.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] *Deus Ex* lead programmer Chris Norden described it as "super flexible" but noted its low execution speed.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Similar to Java, UnrealScript was object-oriented without multiple inheritance (classes all inherit from a common Object class), and classes were defined in individual files named for the class they define.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Unlike Java, UnrealScript did not have object wrappers for primitive types.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Interfaces were only supported in Unreal Engine generation 3 and a few Unreal Engine 2 games.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] UnrealScript supported operator overloading, but not method overloading, except for optional parameters.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] At the 2012 Game Developers Conference, Epic announced that UnrealScript was being removed from Unreal Engine 4 in favor of C++.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Visual scripting would be supported by the Blueprints Visual Scripting system, a replacement for the earlier Kismet visual scripting system.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Verse was created along with UEFN by Epic Games with the aim of creating a programming language that allows UEFN creators to develop complex games and systems for the Fortnite Multiverse.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Simon Peyton Jones, known for his contributions to the Haskell programming language, joined Epic Games in December 2021 as Engineering Fellow to work on Verse with his long-time colleague Lennart Augustsson and others.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Conceived by Tim Sweeney, it was officially presented at Haskell eXchange in December 2022 as an open source functional-logic language for the Fortnite metaverse.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] A research paper, titled *The Verse Calculus: a Core Calculus for Functional Logic Programming*, was also published.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] The language was eventually launched in March 2023 as part of the release of the Unreal Editor for *Fortnite* (UEFN) at the Game Developers Conference.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] It is available to all Unreal Engine users.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] With Unreal Engine 4, Epic opened the Unreal Engine Marketplace in September 2014.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] The Marketplace is a digital storefront that allows content creators and developers to provide art assets, models, sounds, environments, code snippets, and other features that others could purchase, along with tutorials and other guides.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Some content is provided for free by Epic, including previously offered Unreal assets and tutorials.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Prior to July 2018, Epic took a 30% share of the sales but due to the success of Unreal and *Fortnite Battle Royale*, Epic retroactively reduced its take to 12%.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Unreal Engine was originally designed to be used as the underlying technology for video games.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] The engine is used in a number of high-profile game titles with high graphics capabilities, including *Hogwarts Legacy*, *PUBG: Battlegrounds*, *Final Fantasy VII Remake*, *Valorant* and *Yoshi's Crafted World,* in addition to games developed by Epic, including *Gears of War* and *Fortnite*.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Polish game developer CD Projekt is also planning to use the engine after retiring their in-house REDengine; their first game to use Unreal will be a remake of *The Witcher*.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Usage of Unreal Engine has been steadily increasing since 2012, from an estimated 17% market share to 28% in 2024, compared to Unity's 50%.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] By sales, Unreal accounts for 31% compared to Unity's 26%, with proprietary engines accounting for a combined 42%, making Unreal the largest engine by units sold.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Unreal Engine has found use in filmmaking to create virtual sets that can track with a camera's motion around actors and objects and be rendered in real time to large LED screens and atmospheric lighting systems.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] This allows for real-time composition of shots, immediate editing of the virtual sets as needed, and the ability to shoot multiple scenes within a short period by just changing the virtual world behind the actors.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] The overall appearance was recognized to appear more natural than typical chromakey effects.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Among the productions to use these technologies were the live action television series *The Mandalorian*, *Westworld* and *Fallout*, and the animated series *Zafari*, *Barney's World*, *Miraculous: Tales of Ladybug & Cat Noir* (as from its sixth season) and *Super Giant Robot Brothers*.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Jon Favreau and Lucasfilm's Industrial Light & Magic division worked with Epic in developing their StageCraft technology for *The Mandalorian*, based on a similar approach Favreau had used in *The Lion King*.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Favreau then shared this technology approach with *Westworld* producers Jonathan Nolan and Lisa Joy.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] The show had already looked at the use of virtual sets before and had some technology established, but integrated the use of Unreal Engine as with StageCraft for its third season.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Orca Studios, a Spanish-based company, has been working with Epic to establish multiple studios for virtual filming similar to the StageCraft approach with Unreal Engine providing the virtual sets, particularly during the COVID-19 pandemic, which restricted travel.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] In January 2021, *Deadline Hollywood* announced that Epic was using part of its Epic MegaGrants to back for the first time an animated feature film, *Gilgamesh*, to be produced fully in Unreal Engine by animation studios Hook Up, DuermeVela and FilmSharks.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] As part of an extension of its MegaGrants, Epic also funded 45 additional projects since around 2020 for producing feature-length and short films in the Unreal Engine.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] By October 2022, Epic was working with several different groups at over 300 virtual sets across the world.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Unreal Engine was used for motion capture in *Lyle, Lyle, Crocodile*.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Unreal Engine has also been used by non-creative fields due to its availability and feature sets.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] It has been used as a basis for a virtual reality tool to explore pharmaceutical drug molecules in collaboration with other researchers, as a virtual environment to explore and design new buildings and automobiles, and used for cable news networks to support real-time graphics.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Some car companies, most prominently including Rivian, use Unreal Engine in their infotainment systems.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] In March 2012, Epic Games announced a partnership with Virtual Heroes of Applied Research Associates to launch *Unreal Government Network*, a program that handles Unreal Engine licenses for government agencies.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Several projects originated with this support agreement, including an anaesthesiology training software for U.S.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Army physicians, a multiplayer crime scene simulation developed by the FBI Academy, and various applications for the Intelligence Advanced Research Projects Activity with the aim to help intelligence analysts recognize and mitigate cognitive biases that might affect their work.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Similarly, the DHS Science and Technology Directorate and the U.S.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Army's Training and Doctrine Command and Research Laboratory employed the engine to develop a platform to train first responders titled *Enhanced Dynamic Geo-Social Environment* (EDGE).
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] In 2024, the seventh generation Ford Mustang was released, which features a 12.4-inch digital instrument cluster and 13.2-inch infotainment touchscreen, powered by the Unreal Engine.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] The state of the Unreal Engine came up in Epic's 2020 legal action against Apple Inc. claiming anticompetitive behavior in Apple's iOS App Store.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Epic had uploaded a version of *Fortnite* that violated Apple's App Store allowances.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] Apple, in response, removed the *Fortnite* app and later threatened to terminate Epic's developer accounts which would have prevented Epic from updating the Unreal Engine for iOS and macOS.
[src:unreal-engine/unreal-engine] The court agreed to grant Epic a permanent injunction against Apple to prevent Apple from taking this step, since the court agreed that would impact numerous third-party developers that rely on the Unreal Engine.
